<!-- ABOUT TSUNAMI -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>About Tsunamis</h2>
  <p>
    A tsunami is a series of extremely large waves caused by sudden movement in the ocean.
    This can occur due to underwater earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, or landslides.
  </p>
  <p>
    Coastal regions like Andaman & Nicobar, Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, Kerala, and Odisha
    are at higher risk.
  </p>
</article>

<!-- WARNING SIGNS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Natural Warning Signs</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Strong earthquake near the coastline.</li>
    <li>Sudden water withdrawal ‚Äî sea moving back unusually fast.</li>
    <li>Loud roaring sound from the ocean.</li>
    <li>Unusual behavior of birds or animals.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- IMD / INCOIS ALERTS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Official Warning System (INCOIS)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Watch:</strong> Tsunami possible ‚Äî stay alert.</li>
    <li><strong>Advisory:</strong> Strong currents expected ‚Äî avoid beaches.</li>
    <li><strong>Warning:</strong> Evacuate coastal areas immediately.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- PREPAREDNESS -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Preparedness Before a Tsunami</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Identify higher ground or evacuation routes near your area.</li>
    <li>Keep an emergency kit with water, food, flashlight, and first-aid.</li>
    <li>Follow coastal authority instructions and warning sirens.</li>
    <li>Know the safe distance: at least 2 km inland or 30 meters above sea level.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<!-- DOs & DON'Ts -->
<article class="content-card">
  <h2>Do‚Äôs & Don‚Äôts During a Tsunami</h2>

  <h3>‚úî Do‚Äôs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Run to higher ground immediately after an earthquake.</li>
    <li>Follow evacuation signs and use stairs (not elevators).</li>
    <li>Carry emergency supplies when evacuating.</li>
    <li>Help children, elderly, and disabled persons first.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>‚ùå Don‚Äôts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Do NOT go near beaches to watch the waves.</li>
    <li>Do NOT return until officials declare it safe.</li>
    <li>Do NOT use vehicles in traffic ‚Äî they can get stuck.</li>
    <li>Do NOT touch damaged power lines.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

